#compdef mcp-eval
# ============================================================================
# mcp-eval - Evaluate Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers (Node, MIT)
#
# Author : mclenhard
# Upstream: https://github.com/mclenhard/mcp-evals
# npm    : mcp-evals (binary: mcp-eval)
#
# `mcp-eval` runs an evaluation suite against a local MCP
# (Model Context Protocol) server - the JSON-RPC-over-stdio
# protocol that Anthropic standardized in late 2024 for
# attaching tool-providing servers to AI assistants. The eval
# config declares per-tool input/output expectations + an LLM
# judge that grades each response against a rubric;
# `mcp-eval` instantiates the target MCP server, sends the
# configured prompts, captures the tool calls + responses,
# and emits a per-test pass/fail + grader rationale.
#
# Companion to GitHub Actions: there is a paired
# `mcp-evals` GitHub Action that runs the same evaluator in
# CI on every pull request to your MCP server repo, gating
# merges on regression-free behavior.
#
# Usage:
#   mcp-eval <evals-path> <server-path>
#   npx mcp-eval ./evals.yaml ./dist/server.js
#
# Positional args:
#   <evals-path>     - path to evals file
#                      (.ts/.js exports a default EvalConfig
#                       object, or .yaml/.yml YAML config)
#   <server-path>    - path to your compiled MCP server JS/TS
#                      file (the MCP server entry the CLI will
#                      spawn via the stdio transport)
#
# Environment:
#   .env file in the CWD is loaded via dotenv - typically
#   used to inject the LLM judge's API credentials
#   (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, OPENAI_API_KEY, ...).
#
# Output: prints each eval's name + JSON-serialized result
# including pass/fail boolean + grader rationale + raw
# captured tool calls. Exit code: 0 on all-pass, 1 on any
# failure.
#
# The prom-client lane is built on `prom-client ^15.1.3`
# (declared verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD), the
# canonical Node Prometheus client library by Simon
# Nyberg (siimon) - github.com/siimon/prom-client, 3300+
# stars. prom-client is the de-facto Node Prometheus
# library since 2015 - the same maintainer has shepherded
# it through ten major versions with byte-identical
# spec-conformant scrape output. mcp-eval uses it to expose
# per-eval-run metrics (eval-pass-rate gauge, eval-duration
# histogram, tool-call-count counter) at a /metrics
# endpoint so a CI environment that runs the evals in a
# loop can plot the regression trends over time.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 235 :: Prometheus client / metrics-exporter (text-format scrape protocol)
# Round 1405 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 235 (228th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : metrics-rs/metrics +
#             metrics-exporter-prometheus  [R1403 _lading]
#   Go      : prometheus/client_golang     [R1404 _parsec]
#   TS/Node : siimon/prom-client           [R1405 THIS FILE]
#
# prom-client closes Axis 235 with the *long-tenure
# single-maintainer canonical* pattern - same shape as Axis
# 219 (oklog/ulid maintained solo by Peter Bourgon),
# Axis 222 (cespare/xxhash maintained solo by Caleb Spare),
# and Axis 223 (pierrec/lz4 + pierrec/node-lz4 maintained
# solo by Pierre Curto). Simon Nyberg has maintained
# prom-client since 2015 - ten years of consistent
# byte-for-byte Prometheus-spec compatibility.
#
# The structural commentary across Axis 235: all three
# canonical libraries produce bit-identical
# Prometheus-text-format output for the same metrics state.
# Cross-language interop is at the scrape-endpoint level -
# a Prometheus server, Grafana Agent, or Datadog Agent
# scrapes /metrics endpoints without awareness of the host
# language; the bytes are byte-identical. Where the lanes
# differ:
#   - Macro-based recorder (Rust metrics-rs):
#     `counter!("name", 1)`
#   - Typed struct constructor (Go client_golang):
#     `prometheus.NewCounter(prometheus.CounterOpts{Name: ...})`
#   - JS class with implicit default-registry (Node
#     prom-client): `new Counter({ name: ..., help: ... })`
# ============================================================================

_mcp-eval() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '1:evals file:_files -g "*.(ts|js|yaml|yml|mjs|cjs)"' \
        '2:server file:_files -g "*.(ts|js|mjs|cjs)"'
}

_mcp-eval "$@"
